items.synopsis: The Matildas have ended their record-breaking World Cup journey with a physical 2-0 loss to Sweden in the third-place playoff. Follow all the post-match updates in our live blog.

title.children: Matildas finish their stunning World Cup journey with a physical 2-0 loss to Sweden in the third-place playoff

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It doesn't feel right for these Matildas players to be so despondent at the end of this tournament, but this match really felt like a bridge too far for this side that punched above its weight throughout. Sam Kerr, hobbled and maybe at 70 per cent, spends a good long while on her haunches. It seems fitting that she and Caitlin Foord end this match wounded and bandaged up. They've given more than their pound of flesh in this tournament and it's just not quite enough. A fourth-placed finish for the 10th-ranked team in the world is absolutely a performance to be proud of and these last two losses don't erase everything that came before and everything it has created, but there are some lost-looking Matildas out there.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: FULL-TIME: The Matildas' World Cup run ends with a 2-0 loss to Sweden

A fourth-placed finish for the 10th-ranked team in the world is absolutely a performance to be proud of and these last two losses don't erase everything that came before and everything it has created, but there are some lost-looking Matildas out there.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: She was on the ground for an age as play went on around her, but the referee couldn't find a spot to pause it. It's Kerr's right calf (not her previously injured one, for the record) and it was a contact injury, which is good news. She copped a knee in the lower leg, so that's better than it just going ping while she was running. Kerr limps back on to thunderous applause. I don't know how much of an impact she'll be able to have with two crocked calves, but she wants to go out on her shield.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 75' Sam Kerr is down!
